<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Nuosu_language&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Dialects">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Dialects">Dialects</span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Yi_words_sign.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/Yi_words_sign.jpg/220px-Yi_words_sign.jpg" width="220" height="302" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Yi_words_sign.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="http://bits.wikimedia.org/skins-1.17/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
A signpost in a public park in <a href="/wiki/Xichang" title="Xichang">Xichang</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sichuan" title="Sichuan">Sichuan</a>, China, showing Modern Yi, Chinese and English text.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Yi_people" title="Yi people">Yi people</a> speak six major languages/dialects:<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<ol>
<li>Northern Yi (Nuosu)<a href="http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=iii" class="external autonumber" rel="nofollow">[1]</a></li>
<li>Western Yi (Lalu)<a href="http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=ywt" class="external autonumber" rel="nofollow">[2]</a></li>
<li>Central Yi (Lolopo)<a href="http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=ysp" class="external autonumber" rel="nofollow">[3]</a></li>
<li>Southern Yi (Nisu)<a href="http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=nsd" class="external autonumber" rel="nofollow">[4]</a></li>
<li>Southeastern Yi (Nasu)<a href="http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=yig" class="external autonumber" rel="nofollow">[5]</a></li>
<li>Eastern Yi (Nasu)<a href="http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=ywq" class="external autonumber" rel="nofollow">[6]</a></li>
</ol>
<p>These 'dialects' are mutually unintelligible. Northern Yi is the largest with some two million speakers, and is the basis of the literary language.</p>
